  "prompt": "What is the time complexity for reversing a string through recursion?",
  "response": "The time complexity for reversing a string through recursion is **O(n)**, where n is the length of the string.\n\nHere's why:\n\n* **Each recursive call:**  Each call to the recursive function effectively processes a single character of the string (or a portion of it).  It does a constant amount of work: manipulating strings (slicing in many implementations), and making a recursive call.\n\n* **Number of calls:**  The recursion depth is proportional to the length of the string.  For example, if you're reversing the string by repeatedly taking the last character and appending it to the reversed rest of the string, you'll have `n` recursive calls.\n\n* **Total work:**  Since each call does O(1) work (constant time), and you have `n` calls, the total time complexity is O(n * 1) = O(n).\n\n**Example (Python):**\n\n```python\ndef reverse_string_recursive(s):\n  if len(s) == 0:\n    return s\n  else:\n    return reverse_string_recursive(s[1:]) + s[0]\n\n# Example Usage:\nmy_string = \"hello\"\nreversed_string = reverse_string_recursive(my_string)\nprint(reversed_string)  # Output: olleh\n```\n\nIn this example, with each recursive call, `s[1:]` is a string slice, which *can* take O(k) time where k is the size of the substring. However, many Python implementations optimize string slicing to be effectively O(1) if they're simply creating a \"view\" into the original string rather than copying data.  Even if slicing is O(k), the overall time complexity remains O(n) because the sum of k over all recursive calls is still proportional to n.\n\n**Space Complexity:**\n\nIt's important to note that the *space* complexity of this recursive approach is also **O(n)** due to the call stack. Each recursive call adds a frame to the call stack, and in the worst case, the stack will grow to a depth of `n`.\n\n**Alternative Iterative Approach:**\n\nAn iterative approach to reversing a string (e.g., using a loop and swapping characters) also has a time complexity of O(n), but it typically has a *space* complexity of O(1) because it doesn't use a deep call stack.  Therefore, the iterative approach is generally preferred for reversing strings, especially for longer strings, due to its better space efficiency.\n",
